## Domain-Driven Design

### Entities

Domain entities are plain TypeScript classes or interfaces. They must be **framework-agnostic** — no AWS SDK, no DynamoDB, no HTTP.

```typescript
// src/domain/models/Foo.ts
export interface Foo {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  createdAt: string;
}
```

Use classes when the entity has behavior or invariants to enforce:

```typescript
export class Foo {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly createdAt: string;

  constructor(props: { id: string; name: string; createdAt: string }) {
    if (!props.name || props.name.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new ValidationError('name is required');
    }
    this.id = props.id;
    this.name = props.name.trim();
    this.createdAt = props.createdAt;
  }
}
```

### Repository Interfaces

Define repository contracts in the **domain layer**. Infrastructure implements them.

```typescript
// src/domain/repositories/IFooRepository.ts
import { Foo } from '../models/Foo';

export interface IFooRepository {
  save(foo: Foo): Promise<void>;
  findById(id: string): Promise<Foo | null>;
  findAll(): Promise<Foo[]>;
}
```

### Value Objects

Use value objects for concepts with no identity but specific validation rules:

```typescript
export class Email {
  readonly value: string;

  constructor(raw: string) {
    const normalized = raw.trim().toLowerCase();
    if (!/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(normalized)) {
      throw new ValidationError('Invalid email address');
    }
    this.value = normalized;
  }
}
```

