## Application Layer

Application services orchestrate domain logic. They:
- Receive plain input objects (not AWS event objects)
- Validate input using validators
- Instantiate or retrieve domain entities
- Call repository interfaces
- Return plain objects (not domain entities directly)

```typescript
// src/application/services/fooService.ts
import { v4 as uuidv4 } from 'uuid';
import { IFooRepository } from '../../domain/repositories/IFooRepository';
import { Foo } from '../../domain/models/Foo';
import { validateCreateFoo } from '../validators/fooValidator';
import { FooRepository } from '../../infrastructure/dynamodb/FooRepository';

const repository: IFooRepository = new FooRepository();

export async function createFoo(input: unknown): Promise<{ id: string }> {
  const validated = validateCreateFoo(input);

  const foo = new Foo({
    id: uuidv4(),
    name: validated.name,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  });

  await repository.save(foo);

  return { id: foo.id };
}
```

**Rules:**
- Services receive `unknown` input and validate it before use
- Services must not import `aws-lambda`, `@aws-sdk/*`, or DynamoDB directly
- Each service function has a single responsibility
- Return types must be fully typed (no `any`)

